Someone once told me he wished I was more meek. 🙄That comment instantly annoyed me because I associated meekness with weakness. I thought strength meant boldness and courage meant roaring truth.
I [[ realize now ]] that in putting my trust in ✨Jesus✨, He already began growing my “meekness”, while simultaneously maturing my gift of ‘boldness’.
As this relational trust grew, naturally I began surrendering over my anxieties + fears + frustrations + relationships ALL over to Him. In doing that, it prevents us from giving way to quick or fretful anger and fear. Instead, we give place to wrath and hand our cause over to God to let him justify us [[ IF ]] He chooses.
As we patiently wait on His timing + His good power💥 + His grace to work things out in the best ways for [[ HIS ]] glory and for [[ OUR ]] good, I truly see how “Blessed are the meek, for they shall inherit the earth” Mat5:5.
Meekness allows us to become reasonable and open to correction. Our hearts soften and our ‘defenses’ begin to drop. ⬇️
Meekness LOVES to learn. I LOVE it when a friend blows harsh truth into my face because that’s how much they love me. "Wounds from a friend can be trusted, but an enemy MULTIPLIES kisses."😘🙅🏻
When someone calls out my sin in love, I’m in a posture of wanting that deep conviction to grow my dependency on God’s grace. I don't want my own way.
The quietness + openness + vulnerability of meekness is very beautiful [[ AND ]] very painful. It goes against all that we are by sinful nature & requires supernatural help.
So, let’s trust + commit our ways to God as He has already begun to help us by assuring our hearts that we are a fellow heirs of Jesus Christ and that the world and everything in it is 🙌🏼OURS🙌🏼!!! @johnstephenpiper
